<script id="wix-first-paint">
    if (window.ResizeObserver &&
        (!window.PerformanceObserver || !PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes || PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes.indexOf('paint') === -1)) {
        new ResizeObserver(function (entries, observer) {
            entries.some(function (entry) {
                var contentRect = entry.contentRect;
                if (contentRect.width > 0 && contentRect.height > 0) {
                    requestAnimationFrame(function (now) {
                        window.wixFirstPaint = now;
                        dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('wixFirstPaint'));
                    });
                    observer.disconnect();
                    return true;
                }
            });
        }).observe(document.body);
    }
</script>

207);--ricos-custom-quote-margin-inline-start:var(--ricosQuoteMarginInlineStart);--ricos-custom-code-block-line-height:1.5;--ricos-custom-link-text-decoration:inherit;--ricos-custom-link-color:rgba(129,6,207,1);--ricos-custom-link-font-style:inherit;--ricos-custom-link-font-weight:inherit;--ricos-custom-hashtag-text-decoration:inherit;--ricos-custom-hashtag-color:rgba(129,6,207,1);--ricos-custom-hashtag-font-style:inherit;--ricos-custom-hashtag-font-weight:inherit;--ricos-custom-footer-toolbar-padding-inline-start:var(--ricosFooterPadding);--ricos-custom-footer-toolbar-padding-inline-end:var(--ricosFooterPadding);--ricos-custom-editor-add-plugin-button-position-inline-start:var(--ricosAddPluginButtonStart);--ricos-breakout-normal-padding-start:var(--ricosNormalPadding);--ricos-breakout-normal-padding-end:var(--ricosNormalPadding);--ricos-breakout-full-width-padding-start:var(--ricosFullWidthPadding);--ricos-breakout-full-width-padding-end:var(--ricosFullWidthPadding)" data-id="content-viewer"><div class="Arwt-"><div type="first" data-hook="rcv-block-first"></div><div class="_7KJbw"><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="fYinK _32njD WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-foo"><span class="e4Wvi"><br role="presentation"/></span></h3></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block1"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h2 class="Me8pq _32njD WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-n948"><span class="e4Wvi"><span>Summary</span></span></h2></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block2"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-5lg5a"><span class="lMv7L"><span>Since </span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.riskint.blog/post/fancy-bear-s-new-faces" rel="noopener" class="l04dV ro37v" data-hook="WebLink"><span>last posting</span></a><span> on Unit 26165 and Unit 74455, new details have been released publicly and further analysis conducted on Anatoliy Sergeyevich Kovalev and Artem Andreyevich Malyshev. P</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>eriodic review of past collection can often identify new details. Recent findings indicate </span></span><span>Anatoliy Sergeyevich Kovalev is associated with the cyber threat actor commonly referred to as Sandworm (</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>a.k.a. Voodoo Bear, Telebots, Iron Viking)</span></span><span>, and he could have links to Russia&#x27;s Federal Protective Service (FSO). An account using the name and picture of Artem Andreyevich Malyshev, an officer in Unit 26165 (a.k.a. Fancy Bear, APT28), appears on a Russian freelancing website advertising computer services, such as system administrator and programming. </span><span>
</span></span><br role="presentation"/></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block3"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h2 class="Me8pq _32njD WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-fi68a"><span class="e4Wvi"><span>Analysis</span></span></h2></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block4"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-6a5kg"><span class="lMv7L"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Unit 74455</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block5"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-eo0dj"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>On October 15, 2020, the US Department of Justice </span></span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.justice.gov/opa/press-release/file/1328521/download" rel="noopener" class="l04dV ro37v" data-hook="WebLink"><span style="color:#67958f;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>indicted</span></span></a><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> six </span></span><span>Russian General Staff Main Intelligence Directorate (GRU/GR) </span><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>officers from Unit 74455 </span></span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>(a.k.a. Sandworm, Voodoo Bear, Telebots, Iron Viking)</span></span><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> for their alleged roles in computer network operations. The alleged intrusions included the following targets:</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block6"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><ul class="OCMmu WzoeH"><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="iC8vJ" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="" id="viewer-aesj"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>Critical infrastructure in Ukraine (a.k.a. Black Energy, KillDisk, Industroyer);</span></span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="iC8vJ" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="" id="viewer-fjjln"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>A political campaign in France;</span></span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="iC8vJ" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="" id="viewer-2hg0v"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>The country of Georgia; </span></span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="iC8vJ" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="" id="viewer-7i80r"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>International victims of the “NotPetya” malware attacks; </span></span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="iC8vJ" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="" id="viewer-6m5nk"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>2018 Winter Olympic Games (a.k.a. Olympic Destroyer); and </span></span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="iC8vJ" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="" id="viewer-4981i"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>Investigations of nerve agent attacks that have been publicly attributed to the Russian government.</span></span></span></p></li></ul></div><div type="bulleted_list" data-hook="rcv-block7"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-ftk25"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>In February 2020, the US State Department</span></span><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> </span></span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.state.gov/the-united-states-condemns-russian-cyber-attack-against-the-country-of-georgia/" rel="noopener" class="l04dV ro37v" data-hook="WebLink"><span style="color:#67958f;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>reported</span></span></a><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> </span></span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>that </span></span><span>GRU&#x27;s Main Center for Special Technologies (GTsST), in particular Unit 74455 and &#x27;Sandworm&#x27; carried out a disruptive cyber attack against the country of Georgia. Approximately five months later, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>the European Union (EU)</span></span><span style="color:#67958f;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> sanctioned</span></span><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> </span></span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>several cyber threat actors, including Unit 74455. The EU further elaborated on their designation of Unit 74455 by saying it aligns with the threat actor Sandworm. Prior to these details it was not publicly reported that Unit 74455 corresponded to the Sandworm threat actor, and all the intrusions described in the October 2020 indictment were  </span></span><span>perpetrated</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> by Unit 74455.  </span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block8"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-eses"><span class="lMv7L"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block9"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-2hr93"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>The</span></span><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> </span></span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf" rel="noopener" class="l04dV ro37v" data-hook="WebLink"><span style="color:#67958f;background-color:#323639;text-decoration:inherit"><span>Report on the Investigation into Russian Interference in the 2016 Presidential Election</span></span></a><span style="color:#67958f;background-color:#323639;text-decoration:inherit"><span>, </span></span><span style="background-color:#323639;text-decoration:inherit"><span>commonly referred to as the Mueller Report, provide new details on the role Unit 74455 played in interference of the 2016 US Presidential Elections. According to the report, </span></span><span>Unit 74455 assisted with the release of documents stolen by Unit 26165, the promotion of those release documents, and the publication of anti-Clinton content on social media. Furthermore, officers from Unit 74455 separately targeted state boards of elections, secretaries of state, and U.S. companies that supplied software and other technology related to the administration of U.S. elections. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>One of the individuals previously reported on, </span></span><span>Anatoliy Sergeyevich Kovalev is an officer in Unit 74455. </span><span>
</span><span>
</span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Anatoliy Sergeyevich Kovalev</span></strong><span> (Ковалев Анатолий Сергеевич)</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block10"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-1iao9"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>Since last identifying information related to </span></span><span>Anatoliy Sergeyevich Kovalev, hereinafter Mr. Kovlev</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>, one of the VK accounts linked to Mr. Kovalev has been deleted. It is unclear why only one of the two previously linked accounts is deleted, but the account used the alias Nikita Abramov. The deletion of the account inspired further analysis on the other active account.</span></span><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> </span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block11"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="iwMEp" id="viewer-8k02u"><div class="rxF05 qTNqm"><figure class="XObdu"><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-61og3"><span class="lMv7L"><span>
</span><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>One of the</span></span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> pictures on the active account is the same picture that was observed on the now deleted Nikita Abramov account, as seen in figure 2. The picture shows Mr. Kovalev in a race bib sporting number 155. At the time, the number on the bib was used to cross refence both accounts and confirm their relation to Mr. Kovalev. A newly discovered facial recognition tool identifies if two faces are the same person with some level of certainty. That race bib picture compared to the FBI picture of Mr. Kovalev produced a match with 88% certainty. An overlooked emblem on the race bib also provides new insights into Mr. Kovalev&#x27;s career. </span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block14"></div><div class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-c64jq"><span class="lMv7L"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block17"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-52u"><span class="lMv7L"><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>The emblem on the top right of the race bib is actually the insignia for Russia&#x27;s </span></span><span>Federal Protective Service (FSO). The FSO is a Russian</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> government agency focused on protecting high-ranking state officials, including the Russian President. The picture was posted on the VK account sometime in or around 2013, which would put Mr. Kovalev at 21 or 22 years old in the picture (using the date of birth provided by the FBI). </span></span><span>There is even chance that in or around 2013 Mr. Kovalev either joined or attempted to join the FSO, but by at least 2016 had became a part of Sandworm. Mr. Kovalev appears to have a full career working for the Russian government. However, Mr. Kovalev&#x27;s colleague, Artem Andreyevich Malyshev appears to be venturing into the private sector. </span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block18"></div><div fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></div></div></figure></div></div></div><div type="image" data-hook="rcv-block19"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp RBYiE SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-cotc7"><span class="lMv7L"><span>Figure 3 - FSO logo on Mr. Kovalev&#x27;s clothing</span><span>
</span></span><br role="presentation"/></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block20"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-3302g"><span class="lMv7L"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Artem Andreyevich Malyshev </span></strong><span>(Артём Андреевич Малышев)</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block21"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-fomo3"><span class="lMv7L"><span>Artem Andreyevich Malyshev, hereinafter Mr. Malyshev, has risen through the ranks from a likely </span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.riskint.blog/post/fancy-bear-s-new-faces" rel="noopener" class="l04dV ro37v" data-hook="WebLink"><span>military cook</span></a><span> to an officer in Unit 26165. One of the pictures of Mr. Malyshev that was previously identified on multiple online accounts, possesses a 84% certainty match with the FBI picture of Mr. Malyshev. This same picture has been recently identified on a Russian freelancing website. </span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block22"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div </span><span>A reverse image search of the picture seen in Figure 4 produced an account on a Russian freelancing website. The account is linked to a &quot;Malyshev Artem Andreyevich&quot;, which is the same name as Mr. Malyshev, but with his surname before his given name. The account shows services offered include System Administrator, Programming, IT outsourcing, Web Design, Typing and Printing. The prices for these services are unavailable and need to be requested. Each freelancer account has a rating that uses a scale from one to five, with one being poor and five being great. The account with Mr. Malyshev&#x27;s photo is only rated a 4.1 out 5. There are many other freelancers who have a higher rating, including many with a 5 out of 5. </span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block25"></div><div </span><span>There is not date on the account to assess if it is owned and controlled by Mr. Malyshev. The picture is publicly available and could be used by anyone to create the account. However, I like to think Mr. Malyshev went from hacking the Democratic National Convention, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) and the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) to becoming a run-of-the-mill system admin for you average mom and pop shop</span></span><span>. If Mr. Malyshev was driving Uber he would be suspended with that weak 4.1 rating.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block28"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h2 class="Me8pq _32njD WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-fnte4"><span class="e4Wvi"><br role="presentation"/></span></h2></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block29"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h2 class="Me8pq _32njD WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-1tcg6"><span class="e4Wvi"><span>Conclusion</span></span></h2></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block30"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="a4yOF NlrTp WzoeH SeNKp" dir="auto" id="viewer-147f2"><span class="lMv7L"><span>Revisiting previous analysis can be quite useful for anyone in an analytical profession. In this case, newly released details on Sandworm allow for better attribution of Mr. Kovalev and Unit </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span>74455. Overlooked details in a picture of Mr. Kovalev help understand his career path and possible affiliations with other Russian government organizations. It remains unconfirmed if Mr. Malyshev has or is currently moonlighting as a freelancer, but periodic checks on past collection could be beneficial for identifying new and critical details.</span></span><span style="color:#444444;background-color:#ffffff;text-decoration:inherit"><span> </span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block31"></div></div><div
